uk.gov.gchq.palisade.redirect.service

Class RedirectionMarshall<T>

  • java.lang.Object
    • uk.gov.gchq.palisade.redirect.service.RedirectionMarshall<T>
  • Type Parameters:
    T - the return type of the redirector

    public class RedirectionMarshall<T>
extends java.lang.Object
    A marshall co-ordinates the redirection of requests to a Palisade Service using a Redirector that encapsulates the business logic of how to redirect certain requests.

    The host(String) method call is optional, but if called before calling a proxy method, the host string will be passed to the redirector object. Some Redirector implementations may use the originating host argument aid them in their decision. If the host is not set, then null is passed as the host to the redirector object. The host is reset after each call to a redirect method overload. Sample Usage: Assuming a Service named MyService exists as defined below, we set up a simple redirector and show the use of the proxy. 

    
 interface MyService extends Service {

     void someVoidMethod(int a);

     int someIntMethod(String a);
 }

    Assuming some instances of MyService are running, then a redirection request may look like this: 

    
 class Client {

     private final RedirectionMarshall<String> marshall = new RedirectionMarshall<>(...);

     private final MyService fake = marshall.createProxyFor(MyService.class);

     public void someMethod() {
          //we wish to work out where to redirect a method call to someIntMethod:
          StringRedirectionResult result = marshall.redirect(fake.someIntMethod("some string"));

          //the result now contains the destination computed by the redirector instance
          String destination = result.get();

          ...

          //optionally, we can set a host that originated the request for the next request, this will be passed
          //to the redirector object to help it make a decision
          marshall.host("localhost");

          //to redirect a void method, we use a slightly different syntax:
          StringRedirectionResult result = marshall.redirect(() -> fake.someVoidMethod(5));
          ...
     }
 }

      • isRedirectPending

        public boolean isRedirectPending()
        Tests if a redirection has occurred but the result not retrieved yet. This can happen if a redirectory proxy method has been called, but no redirect method overload in this class has been called yet. This is a perfectly valid state for the system to be in. This method allows for the testing of that condition.
        Returns:
        true if a proxy method has been called, but the result not yet retrieved

      • redirect

        public T redirect(java.lang.Runnable call)
        Compute where to redirect the contained method call. This method should be used as directed in the class API usage above. The call parameter should be the method call to a proxy generated by this instance using createProxyFor(Class).

        This overload is provided to allow void methods to be redirected. It can be used by any method call however.

        Parameters:
        call - the call to redirect
        Returns:
        the result value retrieved by the redirector
        Throws:
        java.lang.IllegalStateException - if no redirection result could be retrieved, may happen if a call to the proxy was not made before calling this method
        See Also:
        createProxyFor(Class)

      • host

        public RedirectionMarshall<T> host(java.lang.String host)
        Set the originating host for the incoming request. This is an optional operation and can be used by redirectors as a hint for redirecting. The host field is cleared when redirect(Object) (or a variant) is called.
        Parameters:
        host - the hostname/address that originated the request
        Returns:
        this object
        Throws:
        java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - if host is null or empty

      • createProxyFor

        public <S extends Service> S createProxyFor(java.lang.Class<S> redirectClass)
        Creates a redirection proxy for the given Service class. This should be called as shown in the class API usage above. The returned object is used by clients to "call" methods with the same parameters the real Service method should be called with so the redirector can perform its function.
        Type Parameters:
        S - the type of service
        Parameters:
        redirectClass - the Service class to be redirected
        Returns:
        the proxy
        Throws:
        java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - if redirectClass is not an instance of Service, or it cannot be proxied, e.g. it is a class not an interface
